x4freetext: Energy resolution of the pulsed neutron
ANNRI(BL04) beam line of MLF at J-PARC
Spallation reaction in a mercury target
irradiated with 3-GeV protons (206 kW) . The proton
beams were supplied at a repetition rate of 25 Hz and
in the "double-bunch mode", in which the pulsed
protons consist of two bunches, each with a width of
100 ns, at intervals of 600 ns. Produced neutrons
were slowed down in a supercritical para hydrogen
moderator. Disk chopper with a semicircular shape was
used to cut the low-energy tail of neutron pulse.
The NaI(Tl) spectrometer was used consisting of
The larger detector: 330 mm (diam.) and 203 mm long,
placed at 90 deg. with respect to the neutron beam.
The smaller detector: 203mm (diam.) and 203 mm long,
placed at 125 deg. with respect to the neutron beam.
with 50 mm x 50 mm and a thickness of 1 mm.
loaded glass detector (GS-30:Saint Gobain) was used.
crystalized on a 10-umt pure aluminum foil with a
thickness of approximately 0.2 or 2 um. To reduce the
influence due to thickness nonuniformity, samples
stacked with several 0.2- or 2-umt sheets were used
as Gd samples for the experiments.

T0 = 0.43 micro second for capture and
